"When dipping into online business, a lot of the terminology can seem a bit overwhelming. This blog aims to guide you and help you understand SEO and exactly how SEO works.

SEO is Search Engine Optimisation. Essentially, the process of getting traffic from search engines in a natural way and without advertisements.
Search engine optimisation can get a little bit complicated when it comes to all the different factors that impact your ranking. However, the basic process is not as difficult to understand. Search engines want to provide the best service for their users. This means delivering results on the search engine pages that are not only high quality but also relevant to what the searcher is looking for.
In order to find high quality, relevant materials, search engines will crawl different websites to better understand what the site is about. This helps them deliver more relevant results to those who are searching for certain topics or keywords. Furthermore the search engines will determine how easy it is to navigate and read and then reward user-friendly sites with higher rankings on the search engine results page.
If you have plenty of quality, relevant content pieces on your site, the search engines will be more likely to rank your pages higher on the search engine results page. In addition, the more engaging and effective content you have on your site, the more likely your visitors will be to spend some quality time on your website and maybe even make a purchase. This is why content is so vital for your site.
One important thing to consider when creating content for your site is SEO keywords and phrases. SEO keywords are words and phrases that a search engine user might type in when looking for answers to their questions or relevant products and services. When you create content around these keywords and phrases, you improve your chances of ranking higher for these keywords on the search engine results page.
However, you do need to be cautious with keywords. It’s important to avoid over optimisation. Google and other search engines will penalise your page if it attempts to use keywords too many times throughout the content.
This is just an introduction to SEO and we hope that it has answered some of your most pressing questions."
"If you’ve heard about how vital Google Analytics is for business growth or you’re curious about using Google Analytics to benefit a website, this explainer aims to give you all the answers you’ve been looking for.

Analytics provides vital insights that can help you mould and change the success strategy of your business. Whether you own an ecommerce operation or an informative blog, it’s great to understand the business aspects of it.

Google Analytics gives you the tools to track and understand your customer's behaviour, what they're looking for, and whether your business is addressing their needs. It allows you to use its technology to study your online business so you can cater well to your customers. If you want to deliver effectively to your customers, you need to understand exactly who they are.

One key aspect you can learn from analytics is where your customers have come from. If your clients are mainly coming from their mobile, is it financially viable to investigate a dedicated mobile app?

Another great thing you can get from analytics is which geographical area most of your customers are coming from. Understanding this about your customers helps you formulate marketing strategies and solutions that address their needs. You'll also be able to determine whether there is a growing potential for your products and your services.

You can also target your marketing to benefit new customers without alienating your existing client base.

Google Analytics gives you the information necessary to segment your client base. Each one of your customers is different. They react to your website differently and they perform different actions on it. Using Advanced Segments feature allows you to classify your customers based on certain factors.

When you’re embarking on a new campaign, it’s vital to see if it’s working. To draw attention to your business, you need to create campaigns that reach out to your customers. You also need to measure the impact these campaigns have on your client base. See which emails are bringing people in and which are not so you don’t continue to waste time or money that you could be putting into making your business great.

Google Analytics allows you to add goals and track them. This can help you track how well your business is progressing. By setting goals and studying the results, you can formulate or change existing plans and strategies to make them as effective as possible. You can investigate what’s making people leave your site without converting by using these tools too!"
"Running your business is difficult enough as it is. Finding the time to do everything you need to do, working out what needs to be prioritised and dealing with emergencies is a real challenge. Add trying to focus on marketing on top of that and you’re overwhelmed!

We all know maintaining contact with your target audience is essential for growth but expecting a small business owner to keep in regular contact with their contacts is not realistic. If you’re looking to bridge the communication gap, regular email newsletters are an time efficient, cost effective way of allowing you to communicate with all of your connections and foster and cultivate great relationships.

We understand that business owners don’t have a lot of time. By utilising templates and using content you’ve probably already written if you’re keeping up with your social media, you can create long-lasting relationships with your clients and your contacts. This is why email newsletters are important. They make sure your clients feel like they matter and are a vital consumer.

Don’t worry, though, you don’t have to be a technical whizz to create a newsletter. There’s a lot of great software out there that’s easy to use and creates beautiful, professional newsletters for your clients.

There are very few marketing tools that allow you to communicate with such a huge number of people in such a cost effective way. This means you get an incredible return on investment when utilising newsletters.

Take advantage of technology that allows you to track the results of your email campaign effectively and in real-time. This is pretty much unique to email newsletters and very unlike most other marketing methods.

Being able to monitor who opened your email and which links they clicked on is hugely valuable as it allows you to determine which prospects are engaging with your content. It also allows you to measure exactly which aspects of your content is proving to be of value to your readers.

Whether you’re running a new business and are looking for tips and tricks or you’re curious about what the benefits of a newsletter are for you website, this thorough guide should have answered any and all questions you may have."
"The search engine optimisation (SEO) industry didn’t experience dramatic updates and changes that have been standard in previous years. However, a lot more has changed than you probably realised. If you’re interested in Google changes that took place in 2017, check out this guide.

Smart speakers and digital assistants like Google Now, Siri, and Cortana are changing the way people are searching for information. A much larger percentage of searches are now focused on getting bite-sized pieces of information such as facts, locations, figures, and statuses, as opposed to searching for full-sized web pages. This shift to smaller pieces of information is creating more personalisation especially as these assistants use much more of your search history than Google has historically. This shift means that building a rapport with your clients and customer base is more important than ever.

Another big change has been a growing focus on ‘people also ask’ questions. Smartphone users are far less likely to use their keyboards and Google’s digital assistant is limited in its interpretation. This has caused the value of these suggested searches to go through the roof and so has their prevalence in the search results.

As well as ‘people also ask’ questions, Google results also lifts answers from web pages which draws extra focus to those pages. This may mean that for a web page to be as valuable as possible in 2017 and the years to come, it must be providing answers and solving problems that can’t be solved in a few short sentences.

It was inevitable but it finally happened: 2017 was the year that mobile search traffic outpaced the traffic from desktop searches. Mobile devices and tablets are now the default devices of the typical searcher. This makes it even more vital than ever before to create a site that is just as beautiful and functional on mobile devices as it is on a desktop. There are few things more frustrating than being unable to access a site that has your perfect product because you’re not at your computer."
"Social Media marketing is a great way for businesses to set up new leads and, ultimately, increase your return on investment. Social Media marketing in 2017 is a different beast than it used to be. More and more people understand that Facebook, Instagram and Twitter are invaluable tools in reaching your target audience. This guide aims to offer practical, tangible advice to take advantage of these tools and begin implementing them in your own marketing plans.

<strong>Use Snapchat</strong>
About 10 billion snaps are watched per day by 100 million users. That’s a huge number of people! Snapchat allows users to add a logo or design to their snaps and your business could benefit from these cost-effective interactive marketing tools. It costs around $5 to create a Geofilter for your brand or event.

<strong>Get Specific on Facebook</strong>
Facebook’s ad manager tool allows you to create an audience based on very specific criteria. One of the more useful of which is the ability to target by Life Events. If your business works with services perfect for weddings, you can ensure you advertise to the recently engaged as they are most likely to be interested in your products.

You can also target people based on a huge number of criteria: from interests, recent behaviour, estimated income, relationship status to education level and many more. You can use these types of filters can help you narrow down your audience so you’re only focusing on people likely to be interested in your services or products.

<strong>Make it Look Good</strong>
It sounds obvious but you need to ensure your advertisements actually make people want to click through. Make it striking and interesting but still keep your potential customers relaxed enough to actually want to visit your site.

<strong>Take Advantage of Remarketing</strong>
The most likely people to buy your products are people that have purchased or shown interest in them before. Display items they showed interest in before (by adding to their cart for example) to entice them back to your site. This is a great way to have another chance at converting interest into an actual sale."
"To perform well online, a website needs more than pretty pictures and a beautiful layout (though, of course, those help). This guide should help you ensure you make the right decisions and avoid some of the usual problems so you can have the best website launch campaign possible.

<strong>Create Quality Content</strong>
Before you launch, ensure you have a few pieces of quality content ready to go so your clients see excellent pieces that are valuable to your niche.
From How-to guides to FAQs or even a glossary of industry terminology, make sure the content you’re showcasing is great.

<strong>Utilise SEO Expertise</strong>
Use your keywords in strategic areas of your page. Consistently add fresh, unique new content that also utilises keywords that are right for your business and sector. Also, it is vital that your site is mobile and tablet compatible. You don’t want to shut out a huge section of potential clients and customers who don’t initially visit your site through a computer.

<strong>Install Google Analytics</strong>
Google Analytics is a free tool that can help you discern which of your strategies are working and, more importantly, which aren’t. By installing the program, you can see how many visits your site is getting and where the traffic is coming from.

<strong>Utilise Google Search Console</strong>
If you add your site, you’ll be able to use a variety of tools that are designed to manage the health of your site in terms of search engine optimisation. If there are any issues with your site, you’ll be notified so you can make sure your site is reaching its potential.

<strong>Set up a Pre-Launch Page</strong>
If your site isn’t ready to go live just yet, that doesn’t mean your website should just sit empty. Promote the launch with a countdown page and build anticipation and excitement for your new venture."
"Whether you’re running a small business or a larger venture, your website is equally as vital for your growth.

One of the most important aspects of a company’s brand is their website. However, just having a website isn’t all that matters anymore. Companies and organisations need to take the layout, design and user experience into account too! Building a website or ecommerce store has never been easier, which is why ensuring your clients have a great experience on your site matters more than ever.

<strong>Tell Your Story</strong>
Your potential clients and customers are interested in you and your organisation’s story. When people feel an emotional connection to you, they’re more likely to pursue their interest in your brand further.

<strong>Tell People who you are and what you do</strong>
Having a beautiful website matters but clients need to know what you’re offering. By making your services clear, you’re giving potential customers the confidence in your ability that they’re looking for.

<strong>Ensure your Website has a Responsive Design</strong>
Take into account that not everyone will be visiting your website from a computer. In this day and age, more and more people need a website to function beautiful on their phone and their tablet too. Ensure your website is inviting to a wide range of people by adapting your site for everyone.

<strong>Prioritise the Customers’ Experience</strong>
Make sure your clients don’t have the trawl through vast amounts of content to understand what you do. Having multiple videos might be a good idea or it might make the site more difficult to navigate. Ensure your clients can easily access all the information they might need to be confident about working with you.

<strong>Tell Your Clients Why You’re Different</strong>
You’ve told your clients WHAT you do but have you told them why they should come to you rather than a competitor? That’s a vital part of any marketing especially your website. Show your potential customers that you’re not just another provider; you’re the right one for them.

<strong>Ensure Your Call to Action is Clear</strong>
If clients have to search for a way to contact you or get your products, your website isn’t doing its job! Make it clear what you’re offering and how your potential customers can get it. By being transparent about how your clients can get more information, you keep that emotional connection you gained from telling your story too."
"For those looking to create a successful, worldwide business using nothing but a computer and an internet connection, online businesses have become a veritable gold rush in the past few years. Social Media has created a whole new sector of entrepreneurship based on people’s ability to sell themselves and their own success!

However, learning how to start an online business from home can be a lot more difficult than it looks. You can barely go on Facebook or Instagram without seeing dozens of ads promising to teach you the secrets of the trade. 2.5 billion people log onto the internet every day so we’re offering tangible advice that actually works. You don’t need to rely on gurus to build a business on your own terms.

<strong>Focus</strong>

Focus on figuring out what you want to do and who you want to serve.  There is an information overload out there but how much of this can actually help you where you are? Unsubscribe from email lists that waste your time and don’t offer you real help and guidance, take a break from constant learning and dedicate your energies and existing knowledge into growing your business.

<strong>Build an Audience</strong>

So you have a beautiful website, a great product or a fantastic service but you’re still not making money? The answer could lie in building an audience. When starting a business in the UK, it’s a good idea to build relationships with other business owners who can help you find the customer base for you and your services. Guest post on blogs, feature on a podcast that is in need of your expertise and start writing for large author sites. All these steps will ensure you expand your potential customer base and find an audience that is interested in your skills and your business.

<strong>Create and Develop and Monetisation Plan</strong>

Once you’ve created an audience, it’s time to implement a strategy to generate some income. Plan what products and services you’re planning to sell your clients and customers and use your exposure to sell your offerings and grow your business.

<strong>Refine Your Plan</strong>

Even with the best of planning and intentions, nothing really beats trial and error when it comes to building your online business. This will help you find out what works for you and what doesn’t so you can cut the latter and keep improving on the former,

<strong>Launch</strong>

Now you’ve laid the groundwork, gained fans and interest in your products and services, create launches for any expansions or new products.

Starting an online business isn’t easy. However, we believe these tips will give you the best possible springboard for your new venture."
